	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_495929">I've known about this for a while, but with PC Gamer testing out the DRM with their review copy of Assassin's Creed II I decided to gather the information from the fallout in one post so Safehousers know what they're getting into if they decide to purchase UbiSoft titles in the future (starting with Settlers 7 and Assassin's Creed 2):<br />
<br />
It started with <a href="http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=235290&amp;site=pcg" target="_blank">this blog</a> from PC Gamer.  It basically tests what happens if your connection goes down while playing the game, or wanting to play the game when your internet connection (or the UbiSoft server) is down.  Trying to start the game will give you an error message.  If the connection drops the game will stop, and if you are able to reconnect you'll end up at the last checkpoint you encountered before the connection dropped.  <br />
<br />
ArsTechnica <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gaming/news/2010/02/ubisoft-details-drm.ars" target="_blank">got a response</a> from UbiSoft regarding the loss of the connection, and a <a href="http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=235596" target="_blank">second PC Gamer Blog entry</a> goes into a good amount of detail about the DRM in a Q&amp;A type of setup. Other sites have had similar articles, but they use the links I've supplied above as their source.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
