    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_495931">Yeap... this is looking like another one of my &quot;paid $XX to have to pirate it&quot; games. Don't get me wrong, I'll pay for the game if I get it... I'll just never install it from the discs and use whatever countermeasures the cracking scene comes up with to eliminate the DRM.<br />
<br />
It's sorta a bastard hybrid of what everybody else on the net is saying I think =P <br />
<br />
The truly interesting thing about this, is that it punishes people who don't have an internet connection (or who can't use it 24/7, i.e.: The dial up users still left out there) or those who have less than reliable connections like satellite or cellular connections... or those with bandwidth caps every month. You know, the people who are well known for pirating every title that comes out. You are basically required to be ABLE to pirate the game in order to play it, and if you are incapable of pirating it due to your internet connections, you'll be pretty much incapable of playing the game you legally purchased due to this DRM. Go go Ubisoft.<br />
<br />
I still think the best way to deal with this is rather than just pirate the game like everybody else who is up in arms about this is saying, is to purchase it, and keep their tech support lines tied up with constant calls about the DRM. Vote with THEIR wallet, make it more expensive to support this horrible idea than it would be to not have it there in the first place.</div>
