    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">But you are not supporting their decisions on a certain form of media. While I understand your perspective, in the end you are only punishing yourself. So the compromise is to simply not support the media with the DRM. <br />
<br />
The reality is this, nothing you do is going to make much of a difference one way or the other. So you can be mad at Ubisoft all you want, but at the end of the day you end up not playing a good game. Not just this game per se, but in general. So in the end, the smart (legal) thing to do is to buy the game on console, go to the official forums and express your discontent (In an intelligent and non vulgar manner) and enjoy the game. I don't disagree that what Ubisoft is pulling here is complete crap. Consoles are just as hacked (well the 360 and wii are) as PC's and yet they don't have to deal with DRM. Simple fact is that DRM doesn't, has never and never will work. It has been proven over and over to be an entirely failed concept. Sadly we will, every once in a while have to deal with some random drm scheme that will usually last no more then 1 or 2 titles.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>You're still giving them your money even if you are pissed off about the other product, more money than what you'd pay if you got the PC version. Companies should not be supported at all if they are going to just sit there and want to screw a section of their playerbase over with stupid stuff like this. Whats worse is that they don't do something to the same effect for the console versions of the game, the Xbox 2 at least since the PS3 still isn't fully cracked afaik.</div>
