    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_495972">On the subject of pirating,<br />
<br />
I believe that the source of the debate is because of the fact that pirating a PC game is not stealing something physical but rather digital. There is a difference in my mind still between stealing bread from a supermarket than stealing a PC game from a collection of corporations. Stealing bread gets an immediate immoral signal, while downloading something digital from the net seems different. I know it is not moral, but it's still different.<br />
<br />
Furthermore, here in Israel in a country where pirating is VASTLY more common than the US, I can provide a perspective:<br />
<br />
People pirate because they have the option, and because there are no precautions. <br />
<br />
If you really needed a car, and you could just take it from Ford without no one ever knowing, and you were absolutely guarenteed you'd never get caught, would you take it? I bet alot of people would say yes. And it is obvious why. This question is a moral boundary some people would cross. This is exactly the same question as whether you would pirate Assassin's Creed II. There are no precautions whatsoever.<br />
<br />
There are no precautions... However, people also pirate simply because they can. For example here in Israel people not only pirate PC games which cost 50 to 60$, people also pirate iPhone games which cost 1 to 2$. Why would someone steal something that costs a dollar? Really, do you steal Coca-Cola cans as well? Someone who owns an iPhone obviously doesn't steal Coca-Cola cans, so the answer is simply because they can, simply because pirating an iPhone game <b>is so easy!</b> If the option exists, people will take it. Why pay when you don't have to?<br />
<br />
This is why I believe DRM <b>are a good thing.</b> People say &quot;meh, pirates will always find a way&quot;. This is not correct. Not <b>all</b> pirates will. The harder you make it to pirate, the more technical knowledge the pirate must have, and the less piracy you will encounter. I am all for &quot;draconian&quot; DRM if this is what saves the industry, because PC gaming is not in a good place compared to XBox360 or PS3.<br />
<br />
If you've ever encountered protection that is used for applications like Maya or 3DMax, where licenses cost thousands of dollars... Well, I wish PC games had that kind of protection. I say the more DRM and software protection the better! (This is also because I am a developer myself, so I'm kind of biased <img src="images/smilies/emote_smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smile" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
Peace out. Don't let this debate get too heated eh <img src="images/smilies/emote_smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smile" class="inlineimg" /></div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
