    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_495995">I've been in this debate before...<br />
<br />
All i'm going to add is that the harder you make it to pirate, the better chance the company has of making money.  Whether the amount of money spent to make this so is more or less than the money lost by not having any anit-piracy protection, is another question.<br />
<br />
But in a sense he's right... people will pirate regardless if they can.  Take away that appeal (by logical sense) and piracy is halted or at least vastly slowed.  The only problem is, more and more people will pirate the game because it's become easier.<br />
<br />
My whole problem with piracy is the simple fact that those who do it and don't seem to think there's anything wrong or immoral about it.  Just because you don't or can't get caught doesn't make the crime any less legal or moral...<br />
<br />
And this whole DRM thing hurts the paying customers more imo.  As it becomes more of a hassle for them.  But then again, if you had to walk through a security checkpoint to get a big mac, you would or wouldn't depending on how good that damn burger was....</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
