    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_495997">My problems with DRM come from the position of one who buys her games. I.e. my problem comes when the DRM starts interfering with my ability to play a legally purchased new (by that I mean not used, I don't mean necessarily shiny new release) game.<br />
<br />
If your DRM is requiring things that I see as being absurd:<br />
if it wants to tell me that because I have program X installed I can't play,<br />
if it wants to make it so that I cannot play unless their servers are up even though my game is single player,<br />
if I have to struggle to get the game to install despite meeting every listed system requirement and having a valid CD code,<br />
if it requires me to register my absurdly low undeauthorizable installs only on a website that's so unfriendly to it's human users it could have been designed by skynet and makes it a 3+ hour experience with no guarantee of resolution...<br />
<br />
...then we have a problem. Namely, you the developer has a problem, I just have hatred. For you. For ruining the experience I paid close to 100 bucks for before I even get to experience most of your game. See there's also usually a solution. It's called &quot;get the pirated cracks that fix the stupid DRM crap locking me out of my bought game&quot;. The more you piss me off, the less likely I become of picking up the next game you put out. No, really, thanks. There's pirates out there playing the game with no troubles faster than I am, because your DRM is making the experience a nightmare for me. I'm so glad you're really trying to provide incentive to be honest. It's so totally working. (Bioware is excluded from this sarcasm due to their free-with-new-game DLC approach lately, except for the website part - your websites suck guys, I mean worse than your male romance option for female characters suck, which is a lot of suck)<br />
<br />
I've gone without some games that I might otherwise have checked out because they had a specific DRM that's bent me over in the past and ****ed me up the ass before after I spent a lot of money on the game it rode in on. I'm not paying 100 bucks for a frustration experience. If a game is to include it it should have the decency of having the frustration experience be the gameplay like every self-respecting European CRPG does! If I wanted to pay that much to have someone jerk me around for being an honest person I could ... ok, I'm coming up with nothing as comparison since pretty much everywhere else if you shell out, you get the service people who don't shell out don't get. Either way there's a limited number of games I can shell out the 100 or so bucks it will cost each year - the more of a no-lubed ass****er the DRM riding your game is, the less likely I am to spend that on your game.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
